{
  "action_id": "331",
  "action_title": "Use selective harvesting/logging instead of clearcutting",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nSix studies of seven from the USA and Canada found that some species were more abundant in selective-logged forests, whilst others were less abundant, compared to both control stands and other managements. One study found that there were no consistent differences between selectively harvested and clearcut stands.\nA replicated study from the USA found a lower species richness of cavity-nesting birds in snags in selectively-logged stands, compared to clearcuts.\nA replicated study from the USA found that brood parasitism of two species by brown-headed cowbirds was higher in harvested stands compared to controls, but it was lower for two others."
}

{
  "query": "How do different partial harvesting methods in USA forests compare to clearcutting in their impact on salamander populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "According to research studies in USA forests, several partial harvesting methods have been compared to clearcutting for their impact on salamander populations. A meta-analysis of 24 studies in North America found that partial harvest, which included thinning, shelterwood harvesting, and harvesting groups of trees, resulted in smaller reductions in salamander populations than clearcutting (Action 852, 851, 844). \n\nFor thinning, studies found mixed effects on salamander abundance compared to clearcutting, with some showing higher abundance in thinned forests while others found mixed results depending on species, life stage and time since harvest. Specifically, emigrating salamanders used thinned forest significantly more than clearcuts, though thinning decreased the body condition of ensatina salamanders 10 years after harvest (Action 852).\n\nShelterwood harvesting compared to clearcutting resulted in higher, similar or initially higher and then similar salamander abundance in three USA studies (Action 851). However, harvesting trees in small groups did not result in higher amphibian or salamander abundance compared to clearcutting in three USA studies (Action 844).\n\nLeave-tree harvesting, where a low density of trees is left during harvest, did not result in higher salamander abundance compared to clearcutting in two USA studies (Action 846). All partial harvesting methods studied (thinning, shelterwood, group harvesting, and leave-tree harvesting) decreased salamander abundance compared to unharvested forest areas and affected reproductive parameters such as the proportion of female salamanders carrying eggs and juveniles (Actions 852, 851, 844, 846).",
